Document: Introduction to Godot  
Path: godot/getting_started/introduction/introduction_to_godot.rst  
Summary: Overview of Godot's integrated tools and external support options.  

Godot comes with a fully-fledged game editor with integrated tools to answer the most common needs. It includes a code editor, an animation editor, a tilemap editor, a shader editor, a debugger, a profiler, and more. The team strives to offer a feature-rich game editor with a consistent user experience. While there is always room for improvement, the user interface keeps getting refined.  

External Tools Support:  
- Importing 3D scenes designed in Blender  
- Plugins for coding in VSCode and Emacs for GDScript and C#  
- Support for Visual Studio for C# on Windows
---CHUNK---
Document: introduction_to_godot
Path: godot/getting_started/introduction/introduction_to_godot.rst
Summary: Overview of supported programming languages and engine extensibility options in Godot

Godot supports two primary scripting languages for game development: GDScript and C#. GDScript is a lightweight, Python-inspired language designed specifically for Godot with tight engine integration. C# is also supported and widely used in the game industry. Both languages allow developers to create gameplay logic and game features through standard scripting.

For high-performance code or third-party integration, Godot provides GDExtension technology. This system enables writing performance-critical code in C++ or other supported languages without requiring engine recompilation. GDExtension is particularly useful for integrating external libraries, SDKs, and custom modules into the engine.

The Godot engine is completely open source and free to use. This allows developers to directly modify and extend engine functionality by adding custom modules or features. The open-source nature of Godot provides maximum flexibility for advanced users who need to implement specialized systems or integrate unique technologies.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to Godot  
Path: godot/getting_started/introduction/introduction_to_godot.rst  
Summary: Prerequisites for using Godot, emphasizing programming foundations and object-oriented concepts.  

Godot is a feature-packed game engine with thousands of features requiring good programming foundations to use effectively. While the engine aims for accessibility, understanding programming principles will greatly enhance your experience. Godot relies on object-oriented programming, so familiarity with concepts like classes and objects is essential for efficient coding.  

If you're new to programming, GDQuest's *Learn GDScript From Zero* is a free, open-source interactive tutorial designed for absolute beginners. It is available as a desktop application or in the browser. We will provide additional Godot-specific learning resources in doc_learning_new_features. The next section will cover the engine's essential concepts.